Cicero, who always speaks of him in terms of warmest praise, studied law under his instruction. He was praetor 121 n. c, and consul 117. He is usually known by the title of augur. Parmos Coeranus Sermo Annrmarvos, though not an interlocutor in the dialogue, yet deserves mention as the one whose opinions are ostensibly presented. He was the son of L. Paulus Aemilius, the grandson hy adoption (through his elder son) of the elder Scipio Africanus, and the foremost man of his time. So early in life did he make manifest his pre-eminent ability, that, in order to give him the conduct of the third war against Carthago, the laws were suspended to allow of his election as consul before the legal age.
